  "prompt": "What are stars made out of?",
  "response": "Stars are primarily composed of hydrogen and helium, the two lightest and most abundant elements in the universe. Here's a more detailed breakdown:\n\n1. Composition:\n- About 70-75% hydrogen\n- About 24-25% helium\n- Trace amounts of heavier elements like carbon, oxygen, nitrogen, and iron\n\n2. Physical state:\n- Stars exist in a plasma state, where atoms are stripped of their electrons\n- Extremely high temperatures and pressures cause nuclear fusion in the star's core\n\n3. Nuclear fusion process:\n- Hydrogen atoms fuse together to create helium\n- This fusion process releases massive amounts of energy in the form of heat and light\n- This is what makes stars shine and generate their tremendous energy\n\n4. Core vs. outer layers:\n- The core is where nuclear fusion occurs at extremely high temperatures\n- Outer layers are cooler but still incredibly hot compared to Earth's standards\n\nThe specific composition and proportions can vary slightly depending on the star's age, size, and type, but hydrogen and helium are always the primary components.",
